author/description: Recovering diplomat now focusing on both the global and the local.   Views expressed are my own, despite what the haters may think.
text:
Today my timeline is full of pundits advising the Trump Administration to back India's ongoing attempts to reverse #Bangladesh's July Revolution.   What these analysts ignore is that India's misguided policy of providing unquestioned support to a brutal dictator helped lead to the popular uprising.   India has been consistently wrong on Bangladesh, misunderstanding the mood in the country and stoking anti-Indian sentiment.   While U.S. policy in recent years has not been perfect, its standing in Bangladesh is currently much higher than that of India. 

Why would an America First foreign policy choose to back a loser like India?  As events in July and August proved, the people of Bangladesh will choose their own destiny.   The Indians could not keep Hasina in power, and despite the conspiracy theories, no outside hand was responsible for her ouster.   @ChiefAdviserGoB and his government have a popular mandate paid for with the blood of the martyrs of the long July.   Hasina and her cronies are not coming back.   

The choice that the Trump Administration will have in January is simple.  Should the U.S. continue to build a relationship with a reformed and democratic Bangladesh that can be a partner in the Indo Pacific and  beyond?    If so, then there are opportunities for the U.S. to expand trade and investment, people to people ties, and security cooperation with Bangladesh -- before and after elections.   The alternative is for the U.S. to tie itself to India and lose support and influence among the people of Bangladesh for generations (as it did by mistakenly supporting Pakistan in 1971).

India is fond about talking about strategic autonomy.    In this case, the United States should also pursue a similar approach to Bangladesh.   President Trump and his team should pursue U.S. interests vis a vis Bangladesh and not fall for the trap of becoming India's handmaiden.

New Report Says Liberal Women Are Sterilizing Themselves in Response to Trump‚Äôs Election | Cassandra MacDonald, The Gateway Pundit

Liberal women are sterilizing themselves in response to President-elect Donald Trump‚Äôs win earlier this month, according to a new report from Newsweek.
The outlet spoke to five women who are so concerned about losing access to abortions that they are having their fallopian tubes removed over the election results.

‚ÄúIf I am to be denied any rights in the next four (or more) years, I will not give them up without a fight,‚Äù 28-year-old Texas resident Lydia Echols told Newsweek.

A 39-year-old from Washington, who asked to remain anonymous, told the outlet that she has already undergone a bilateral salpingectomy, removing her fallopian tubes, over Trump.

‚ÄúI am not happy that I felt forced into a surgery I did not want to alter my body, I feel like the election tied my hands and forced me to be sterilized‚Äîthat is horrible,‚Äù the unhinged liberal told Newsweek.

‚ÄúI paid way too much attention to the vitriol Trump repeatedly spit during his previous term,‚Äù she continued, ‚Äúand am keenly aware of the people he keeps around him and in his ear, who all seem to see women as incubators and possessions to subjugate.‚Äù

The woman said she scheduled the surgery in October and planned to cancel the appointment if Kamala Harris had won. Her husband already had a vasectomy in 2021.

‚ÄúWith Trump‚Äôs victory, we quickly learned that my choice to cancel the surgery had been taken from me,‚Äù she said. ‚ÄúWe both believed that I had no choice but to proceed to ensure that I can protect my health should I be assaulted during a Trump presidency, should my husband‚Äôs vasectomy fail and/or should my hormonal birth control become inaccessible.‚Äù

‚ÄúThis isn‚Äôt a wanted procedure, but one of necessity due to the politics and subjugation coming our way.‚Äù

Georgia resident Morgan Wood, 24, told Newsweek that she has a consultation to be sterilized on December 5.

‚ÄúI have no idea what Trump will and won‚Äôt follow through on,‚Äù Wood said, ‚ÄúI was already upset when Roe v Wade was overturned. Living in the South, our prospects for protections and resources aren‚Äôt great if they aren‚Äôt otherwise ensured.‚Äù

Wood added, ‚Äútalks of complicating the birth control and abortion access processes even further made this feel like the only option. I need everything handled, and ideally before power begins shifting.‚Äù

Ashley Hedden, 36, of Kentucky, claims to be ‚Äúasexual‚Äù and told the outlet that the only way she would get pregnant would be if she was raped, and wants to be sterilized for that reason.

‚ÄúThe only way I would get pregnant is if I were raped, and I refuse to be forced to carry the result of a man‚Äôs violence against my will,‚Äù she said. ‚ÄúI have seen that this country will not protect people that can get pregnant, and have seen the reports of the deaths of pregnant women that were refused medical care. I refuse to be a person that ends up not being able to get medical care just because I own a uterus with some cells growing in it.‚Äù

Florida resident Eden Ixora, 25, said she decided to get sterilized over a massively viral joke made by podcaster Nick Fuentes in which he said, ‚ÄúYour body, my choice.‚Äù

‚ÄúAll the political noise is what really finalized my decision for me,‚Äù she said. ‚ÄúIt wasn‚Äôt just Trump winning but rather all the online rhetoric that followed.‚Äù

‚ÄúFor me it was a call to action,‚Äù Ixora said. ‚ÄúA need to get this locked in so I don‚Äôt have to live in fear that at any moment some random guy can completely destroy my life. For me the idea of getting pregnant is worse than death. I‚Äôm doing what I can to protect my right to choose. I am choosing me.‚Äù

text:
DELICIOUS: Andrew McCabe Throws a Fit on CNN Over Trump Nomination of Kash Patel | Nick Arama, RedState

As we reported, President-elect Donald Trump has now nominated Kash Patel for the spot of FBI Director.

Patel is a big favorite of Trump supporters and it's also going to be hard to argue that he isn't qualified. He's an attorney who has handled many trials, and served as Chief of Staff at the Department of Defense, Deputy Director of National Intelligence, and Senior Director for Counterterrorism at the National Security Council.

How do you know it's a good pick? All the right people are upset. They know that Patel is not just going to be a status quo, ordinary Republican, and that he's going to clean things up.

Former FBI official Andrew McCabe was throwing a fit on CNN immediately after the announcement. Imagine CNN having the disgraced McCabe on for an opinion about anything, much less about this.

It's a terrible development for the men and women of the FBI and also for the nation that depends on a highly functioning, professional, independent Federal Bureau of Investigation.¬†

The fact that Kash Patel is profoundly unqualified for this job is not even like a matter for debate.

What we should really be thinking about right now is what does this signal in terms of Donald Trump's intent for the FBI?

Such a nomination "can only possibly be a plan to disrupt, to dismantle, to distract the FBI," McCabe said, and "to possibly" use the FBI as a "tool" for Trump's "political agenda."

There is a plan to "disrupt" and "dismantle" -- any further misuse or weaponization of the FBI. This is one of those positions that the people have given Trump a mandate to address, and Patel has made it clear he will turn the focus back on fighting crime again, as he said on the "Shawn Ryan" show.
